{"type":"message","id":"5d509596","parentId":"6ed9da48","timestamp":"2026-04-25T08:20:59.147Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, the desktop app's main.js looks for .env in the app directory, not in Resources. Let me check the main.js again.\n\nLooking at `resolveAppDir()`:\n```javascript\nfunction resolveAppDir() {\n  if (app.isPackaged) {\n    // exe 所在目录\n    return path.dirname(app.getPath('exe'));\n  }\n  return app.getPath('userData');\n}\n```\n\nSo for macOS packaged app, `app.getPath('exe')` is `/Applications/Daily Stock Analysis.app/Contents/MacOS/Daily Stock Analysis`, so `path.dirname` would be `/Applications/Daily Stock Analysis.app/Contents/MacOS/`, and then the `.env` file would be in the `MacOS` directory or the app directory itself.\n\n\nThen `resolveEnvExamplePath()` checks if the app is packaged and constructs the path to `.env.example` in the Resources directory, while `resolveAppDir()` for packaged apps returns the parent directory of the executable path.\n\nThe `envPath` gets set to `appDir + '/.env'`, and since `appDir` is `/Applications/Daily Stock Analysis.app/Contents/MacOS/` for the packaged app, the actual `.env` file would need to be at `/Applications/Daily Stock Analysis.app/Contents/MacOS/.env`, not in Resources. The packaged app expects `.env` in the app bundle's MacOS directory.\n","thinkingSignature":"488d8128be1d91d63311638b5cf387450162d6096728dbb2b48921da5719c0dc"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_pskqgdgsg6cu_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cp \"/Users/ling/Library/Application Support/Daily Stock Analysis/.env\" \"/Applications/Daily Stock Analysis.app/Contents/MacOS/.env\" && echo \"done\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":107,"output":354,"cacheRead":94112,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":94573,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777105250867